Metasploitable2 Installation Guide

Installing Metasploitable2 in VirtualBox

Metasploitable2 is a Linux virtual machine configured to have as many open services and vulnerabilities as possible. You can download it from Rapid7 here. (It’s about 900 MB.)

The zip file contains a virtual hard disk that we will load in VirtualBox. Unzip the file to get started, then open VirtualBox and click New:

Name it something you’ll remember and select a Type of “Linux”, then click next:

Set your desired RAM and CPU settings on the next page, then on the third page, click Use an Existing Virtual Hard Disk File and click on the button to choose a file:

Now click Add

Now click Next and Finish, and you have a freshly installed Metasploitable2 machine in your VirtualBox.

Adding Kali and Metasploitable2 to the same subnet

Now we’ll put your Kali box and the Metasploitable2 box in the same subnet. For convenience, I like to group virtual machines so I can visually see which ones are connected:

To get started, go to File > Preferences and make sure the Expert toggle is set.

Now go to File > Tools > Network Manager and click Create

You’ll get a UAC prompt from Windows. Make sure that you click okay, and you should see an extra “VirtualBox Host-Only Ethernet Adapter” appear in the list. At the bottom, click on the tab for DHCP Server and check the box that says Enable server:

Go back to the adapter tab and toggle Configure Adapter Automatically

Now, return to your Metasploitable2 machine and click on Settings:

Scroll down to Network, and disable Adapter #1 (the default adapter that VirtualBox sets up that’s internet-connected). Instead, click on the tab for whichever adapter you just set up (in my case, it’s adapter #3):

Make sure you set this to Host-only adapter and change the name to your intended adapter. Once you’ve done that, just click OK and repeat the process for your Kali machine. By selecting the same adapter for each machine, they will be using the same DHCP server and will communicate over the subnet, so they will share an internal network.

Assuming you have followed these steps, your Kali and Metasploitable2 boxes should be able to communicate. To confirm this, you can boot up both and run the ip addr or ifconfig commands on both. In my case, VirtualBox’s DHCP server put them in the 192.168.101.0/24 subnet as shown by these outputs:
